column53: Notes
trib is trib-like and seep-like
RHVA found under SWD

surprised it tooke me so long to find a RHVA. Checked the South fork of the seep first. Couldn’t find a RHVA but habitat looked great; coarse substrate and moss mats. Finally found a larvae in the W fork.

has a gradient of 9 at the confluence but then flattens out (5) and gets mucky; dries out after about 5 meters; 9/24/2016-looks pretty dry, still moist, but only water seeping at confluence with channel
short trib coming from an undercut of the really incised channel bank; too short to get a gradient; completley covered by fern and oerhanging bank and branches
short seep, disappears quicklu, low gradient; looked dry on 9/24/2016
went back on 9/10/2016 and it was dry; 30 cm wide, silt and sand, no animals
seep was low gradient, between 1 & 4 degrees. Not much water; ender after around 5 m. Substrate was good, just needs more water.
we started survey at m 11 because the seep wasn’t surveyable before

eyes are just beginning to bulge out; found RHVA around 3 meters up seep (5 toes on back feet, 4 toes on front feet); still has small gills and fin-like tail; seep started looking more like a trib (incised) about where I found the RHVA;pics on phone
RHVA escaped before measurment; found at beginning of seep, trib is subsurface so don’t know distance
found within 30 seconds under duff
Says between 700 and 750; lots of coarse substrate but was found under duff
flag is written as 840; area where found was covered w/ duff; 1 m up trib/seep; right at confluence
flag is written as 840; area where found was covered w/ duff; 1 m up trib/seep; right at confluence
Everything is covered by mucky sand and duff RHVA found under duff; 6 m from trib
.5 meters long, cant follow up, goes subsurface; 9/28/16-still flowing H20, channel becomes very incised immed. After
Habitat is not a seep, intermittant trib or side channel. Channel is deeply incised but isnt currently flowing. 27 m long
area where found was completley covered with duff
first torrent under wet duff
looks nice, surprised no RHVA
lost of the seep is covered by downed wood, found under a piece of wood
1 m long then disapears under trees
short, ~2 m until patch of skunk cabbage

Started following a supposed seep. The second I pulled back a fern I was a RHVA. This seep goes sub surface a few meters up from RHVA. While walking back to measure the dist. From main channel, I realized this was not the original seep. I had followed but iwa a fork and I couldnt figure out where it entered the main channel.
eyes starting to bulge, couldn’t see gills but also didn’t have a bag of water to put it in.

Pretty much whole area torrent found in is covered by a mat of moss (had to pull it back); right at where the valley starts, hill turns into boggy 'open' area, void of ferns and brush. Covered with liverworts, grasses and other forbs; whole area is pretty much a huge boggy seep
Right by SW4; short seep (~2 m), at least part I could see; disappears under downed sitka and brush
there was a small section with substrate but very minimal; RHVA was found on hard clay substrate under a mat of moss; most of this really short seep (~2 meters) is hard clay; pic = male reach 2
found in muck under fern mat and SWD; seep seems to be running dwon an old skid ro ad; can't find an obvioius  connection to the trib. RW found while walking the road alongside the trib
written as 214 on flag and GPS
again there was a good amount of sharp, pointy, pebble sized substrate; found under mat of moss
saved and written as 31; seep is composed of pebble sized jagged rocks, seems out of place, maybe was brought in for roads
Took ~ 3 minutes to find in aggregate from rock, prob from roads
both RHVA were found on the side of seep under wood; had to pull up wood/fern mat, were deep under
This is definitley a fork in the creek but contains seep habitat; torrents found in gravel
Really mucky, clay, fines. No presence of the aggregate material seen in other seeps, followed trib around 10 meters until end
surveyed around 3 meters, no animals, there was some more of the seep I couldn’t get to, to suvey because of downed wood/trees
whole seep was searched, no torrent
9/17/2016-seems too dry now, only moist
seep is coming out from under large old growth log; coars sub but mucky; dark and shaded
no reason shouldn’t be here, decent seep with f ern cover; lots of muck but coarser substrte beneath
very small trib with seepy areas
very short area with water
All RHVA found in same area; pulled out SWD piece and all tumbled out
